reviewText: This copy of a vintage movie was so blurry you could not make out the faces of the actors. the sound track was buffled at best mostly unable to make out what they were saying...I've made better tapes! Total waste of money & I bet this was a bootleg tape !

In one early scene Edgar Buchannan's character is having a bachelor party with his also old buck friends. THe bachelor party is them all sitting in rocking chairs going back and forth! Fortunately once Buchannan meets up with his old pal Brennan things get better from there. Natalie Wood's sister Lana has a small but meaty role in this western dramedy too.

It was fun to see these old characters together--Fred Astaire along with Walter Brennan, Andy Devine, Edgar Buchanan, Chill Wills and others.  If you're not old enough to remember those guys, you probably won't enjoy the movie. My low rating is because the video quality was the worst I have ever seen, and the audio had problems, too.  My suggestion: try it on Prime if you like; but if you have to pay for it, watch something else.

A predictable made-for-TV movie from 1970 featuring a quartet of western veterans and...Fred Astaire! While Astaire looks more like a riverboat gambler than a feared ex-Texas Ranger, it was fun watching him in an unexpected role. The picture quality is not perfect, as if the master has been allowed to degenerate over the years. And the "extra" biography of Astaire contains a big error, saying he appeared in two movies called "Irene Castle" and "The Story of Vernon." He was actually in one film titled "The Story of Vernon and Irene Castle"! Oops. For Astaire fans, it's worth watching.
It was entertaining.  I enjoyed watching because it was light material and made for easy watching.  Acting was good by all.
Just to see this cast of classic western film players together again is well worth the time.  I loved the first one and like this one.
